latestPosts.caption:
Day 2 SDCC recap: not ‘feeling’ so alright’ yesterday. Something I ate the previous night definitely did not agree with my stomach…luckily I know where all the secret bathrooms are at SDCC 🤢

Powered through multiple signings from Torpedo Comics (which has black and white exclusive editions of my Batman 158–booth 1000) to the DC Booth with my Batman writer extraordinaire @jephloeb3 (booth 4544) to an @ebay live streaming offsite near Petco Park with @anzcomics Ali…seeing so many new and old fans (along with more and more of my family and friends who are making it down to the con) brightened up an otherwise queasy day…

Ended up bowing out of attending the Eisner Awards 😣😩 and calling it an early night. Used the opportunity to add more stars (splatter) to a fun Legion piece for a friend. Someday something bigger in the future awaits with these heroes of the 31st century! 🙌

Day 1 SDCC recap! 

Inspired by Elf on the Shelf, had a bit of a giveaways galore yesterday. 

If I look like a newsboy legionnaire it’s because we are celebrating the first decade of DC Comics 1935-1945. It’s how I imagine comic con was like back in the day :) 

Happy Belated birthday, David, on hitting the big 5-0!

I’m not yawning at All American Rejects, I’m yawning because I’m old and tired. 

Be on the look out for my debut album featuring @dan.didio2020 @tomking_tk @boryskit 

Lastly, congrats to my son for hitting high score at the Fortnite  livestream at the DC Booth! #raisedhimright

latestPosts.caption:
Sharing a photo likely from 1998—judging by the watch and the blue-and-white Padres cap that debuted that year. I’m about to start a piece of art for the Comic-Con art auction. Behind me is the organizer of said auction—the one and only Clydene Nee.

Most of you may not know her name—but nearly every comic creator who ever walked Artist Alley at SDCC knew exactly who she was.

Clydene was the heart and soul of Artist Alley. From 1989 on, she was its steady hand, its welcoming smile, its fiercest advocate. Through her company InColor, she helped launch WildStorm and Image in the early ’90s, pulling all-nighters doing digital color and separations to get our books out the door.

She championed new talent before it was fashionable—giving rising stars like Kim Jung Gi their first booth, organizing artist-focused programming, and running the annual art auction to fund interpreters. Everything she did was in service of creators. She gave us space, she gave us voice, she gave us opportunity.

Even as severe health issues took their toll in recent years, Clydene remained kind, determined, and deeply connected to the work and the people she loved.

On the drive down to the show last night—I thought back on all her accomplishments over the many decades she has served SDCC. For someone who didn’t draw or create—she sure made comics a better, lovelier place.

This will be the first Comic-Con without her since 1989. And without her, it won’t feel quite the same. Rest in peace, Clydene.

latestPosts.caption:
Had a blast collaborating with the insanely talented @jorge_jimenez_art on a special diptych variant cover for Batman #1—written by the incredible, critically acclaimed writer Matt Fraction, dropping this September.

Jorge laid out the full composition and illustrated the H2SH side while I tackled the new relaunch side—featuring the main heroes and villains from what’s looking to be a sales-shattering run. 

What made this collab especially interesting? Jorge works predominantly digital while I’m old-school analogue—so capturing the shared mood and atmospheric effects using just pencil and ink was a fun challenge. Jorge also laid out the central Batman figure so I needed to play within the shapes he beautifully laid out and create something that worked well on its own without breaking the overall composition. Huge thanks to @scottwilliamsinks on inks and colorist @tmorey on colors for magnificently bringing it all together. Love how this turned out 💙 Batman #1 on sale September 3rd! It’s 🔥🔥🔥

latestPosts.caption:
Superman is unapologetically a comic book film—and this Superman is unapologetically kind, good-hearted, and hopeful. That spirit comes straight from the comics, but it took writer/director James Gunn to take the creative risk of putting that ideal—and himself—on the line. Right down to saving one very grateful sciurus carolinensis.

Thank you, James, for not only bringing that spirit to life, but for taking the time to thank and acknowledge the comic book creators whose work inspired it all—a gesture that meant the world to us.

Visiting the Superman set was unforgettable. Walking the halls of the Fortress of Solitude… witnessing Superman and Lex face off in Luthor’s gravity-defying penthouse… pure magic.

They say “write what you know.” James did exactly that. The result? Something truly special. Superman is now in theaters—see it on the biggest screen you can 💙❤️💛 #lookup

My variant cover inked by @scottwilliamsinks and colored by @sinccolor for ROBIN & BATMAN JASON TODD #3 with a powerful and moving story by @jefflemire and lush, beautiufl art by @duss005–CAN YOUNG JASON TODD BE SAVED!?! Tried a lighter different approach to this piece than what you would expect highlighting the time this new Dynamic Duo had as Protectors of Gotham!

In-Store Date 8/27 😎
